# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pug-templating
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pug-templating/comparison-of-web-template-engines] The following table lists the various web template engines used in Web template systems and a brief rundown of their features.
[src:pug-templating/getting-started] The general rendering process of Pug is simple.
[src:pug-templating/getting-started] `pug.compile()` will compile the Pug source code into a JavaScript function that takes a data object (called “`locals`”) as an argument.
[src:pug-templating/getting-started] Call that resultant function with your data, and *voilà!*, it will return a string of HTML rendered with your data.
[src:pug-templating/getting-started] The compiled function can be re-used, and called with different sets of data.
[src:pug-templating/getting-started] Pug also provides the `pug.render()` family of functions that combine compiling and rendering into one step.
[src:pug-templating/getting-started] However, the template function will be re-compiled every time `render` is called, which might impact performance.
[src:pug-templating/getting-started] Alternatively, you can use the `cache` option with `render`, which will automatically store the compiled function into an internal cache.
[src:pug-templating/html] Web browsers receive HTML documents from a web server or from local storage and render the documents into multimedia web pages.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML describes the structure of a web page semantically and originally included cues for its appearance.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages.
[src:pug-templating/html] With HTML constructs, images and other objects such as interactive forms may be embedded into the rendered page.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML provides a means to create structured documents by denoting structural semantics for text such as headings, paragraphs, lists, links, quotes, and other items.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML elements are delineated by *tags*, written using angle brackets.
[src:pug-templating/html] Tags such as `<img>` and `<input>` directly introduce content into the page.
[src:pug-templating/html] Other tags such as `<p>` and its corresponding closing tag `</p>` surround and provide information about document text and may include sub-element tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] Browsers do not display the HTML tags, but use them to interpret the content of the page.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML can embed programs written in a scripting language such as JavaScript, which affects the behavior and content of web pages.
[src:pug-templating/html] The inclusion of CSS defines the look and layout of content.
[src:pug-templating/html] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), former maintainer of the HTML and current maintainer of the CSS standards, has encouraged the use of CSS over explicit presentational HTML since 1997.
[src:pug-templating/html] A form of HTML, known as HTML5, is used to display video and audio, primarily using the `<canvas>` element, together with JavaScript.
[src:pug-templating/html] In 1980, the physicist Tim Berners-Lee, a contractor at CERN, proposed and prototyped ENQUIRE, a system for CERN researchers to use and share documents.
[src:pug-templating/html] In 1989, Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system.
[src:pug-templating/html] Berners-Lee specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:pug-templating/html] That year, Berners-Lee and CERN data systems engineer Robert Cailliau collaborated on a joint request for funding, but the project was not formally adopted by CERN.
[src:pug-templating/html] In his personal notes of 1990, Berners-Lee listed "some of the many areas in which hypertext is used"; an encyclopedia is the first entry.
[src:pug-templating/html] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Tim Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:pug-templating/html] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:pug-templating/html] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by CERN SGML, an in-house Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML)-based documentation format at CERN.
[src:pug-templating/html] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML is a markup language that web browsers use to interpret and compose text, images, and other material into visible or audible web pages.
[src:pug-templating/html] Default characteristics for every item of HTML markup are defined in the browser, and these characteristics can be altered or enhanced by the web page designer's additional use of CSS.
[src:pug-templating/html] These formatting commands were derived from the commands used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:pug-templating/html] However, the SGML concept of generalized markup is based on elements (nested annotated ranges with attributes) rather than merely print effects, with separate structure and markup.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML has been progressively moved in this direction with CSS.
[src:pug-templating/html] Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML.
[src:pug-templating/html] The draft expired after six months, but was notable for its acknowledgment of the NCSA Mosaic browser's custom tag for embedding in-line images, reflecting the IETF's philosophy of basing standards on successful prototypes.
[src:pug-templating/html] Similarly, Dave Raggett's competing Internet Draft, "HTML+ (Hypertext Markup Format)", from late 1993, suggested standardizing already-implemented features like tables and fill-out forms.
[src:pug-templating/html] After the HTML and HTML+ drafts expired in early 1994, the IETF created an HTML Working Group.
[src:pug-templating/html] In 1995, this working group completed "HTML 2.0", the first HTML specification intended to be treated as a standard against which future implementations should be based.
[src:pug-templating/html] Further development under the auspices of the IETF was stalled by competing interests.
[src:pug-templating/html] Since 1996, the HTML specifications have been maintained, with input from commercial software vendors, by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:pug-templating/html] In 2000, HTML became an international standard (ISO/IEC 15445:2000).
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML 4.01 was published in late 1999, with further errata published through 2001.
[src:pug-templating/html] In 2004, development began on HTML5 in the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG), which became a joint deliverable with the W3C in 2008, and was completed and standardized on 28 October 2014.
[src:pug-templating/html] It was the first version developed and standardized exclusively by the W3C, as the IETF had closed its HTML Working Group on 12 September 1996.
[src:pug-templating/html] were omitted due to a mutual agreement between the two companies.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML 4 is an SGML application conforming to ISO 8879 – SGML.
[src:pug-templating/html] was reissued with minor edits without incrementing the version number.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML", based on HTML 4.01 Strict) was published as an ISO/IEC international standard.
[src:pug-templating/html] (ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1, Subcommittee 34 – Document description and processing languages).
[src:pug-templating/html] After HTML 4.01, there were no new versions of HTML for many years, as the development of the parallel, XML-based language XHTML occupied the W3C's HTML Working Group.
[src:pug-templating/html] an informal CERN document listing 18 HTML tags, was first mentioned in public.
[src:pug-templating/html] IIIR Working Group as an Internet Draft (a rough proposal for a standard).
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML+ was published by the IETF as an Internet Draft and was a competing proposal to the Hypertext Markup Language draft.
[src:pug-templating/html] It included many of the capabilities that were in Raggett's HTML+ proposal, such as support for tables, text flow around figures, and the display of complex mathematical formulas.
[src:pug-templating/html] but HTML 3.0 did not succeed for several reasons.
[src:pug-templating/html] The draft was considered very large at 150 pages and the pace of browser development, as well as the number of interested parties, had outstripped the resources of the IETF.
[src:pug-templating/html] Browser vendors, including Microsoft and Netscape at the time, chose to implement different subsets of HTML 3's draft features as well as to introduce their own extensions to it.
[src:pug-templating/html] has abandoned any attempt to be an SGML application and has explicitly defined its own "html" serialization, in addition to an alternative XML-based XHTML5 serialization.
[src:pug-templating/html] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its HTML Working Group with clear milestones for HTML5.
[src:pug-templating/html] In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification.
[src:pug-templating/html] The W3C developed a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which was the target date for recommendation.
[src:pug-templating/html] In January 2011, the WHATWG renamed its "HTML5" living standard to "HTML".
[src:pug-templating/html] The W3C nevertheless continued its project to release HTML5.
[src:pug-templating/html] W3C will continue the HTML5 specification work, focusing on a single definitive standard, which is considered a "snapshot" by WHATWG.
[src:pug-templating/html] The WHATWG organization will continue its work with HTML5 as a "Living Standard".
[src:pug-templating/html] The concept of a living standard is that it is never complete and is always being updated and improved.
[src:pug-templating/html] New features can be added but functionality will not be removed.
[src:pug-templating/html] In December 2012, W3C designated HTML5 as a Candidate Recommendation.
[src:pug-templating/html] is "two 100% complete and fully interoperable implementations".
[src:pug-templating/html] In September 2014, W3C moved HTML5 to Proposed Recommendation.
[src:pug-templating/html] meaning the specification process is complete.
[src:pug-templating/html] XHTML is a separate language that began as a reformulation of HTML 4.01 using XML 1.0.
[src:pug-templating/html] It is now referred to as *the XML syntax for HTML* and is no longer being developed as a separate standard.
[src:pug-templating/html] On 28 May 2019, the W3C announced that WHATWG would be the sole publisher of the HTML and DOM standards.
[src:pug-templating/html] The W3C and WHATWG had been publishing competing standards since 2012.
[src:pug-templating/html] While the W3C standard was identical to the WHATWG in 2007 the standards have since progressively diverged due to different design decisions.
[src:pug-templating/html] The WHATWG "Living Standard" had been the *de facto* web standard for some time.
[src:pug-templating/html] The W3C periodically reviews and publishes snapshots of the WHATWG HTML specification as W3C Recommendations.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML markup consists of several key components, including those called *tags* (and their *attributes*), character-based *data types*, *character references* and *entity references*.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML tags most commonly come in pairs like `<h1>` and `</h1>`, although some represent *empty elements* and so are unpaired, for example `<img>`.
[src:pug-templating/html] The first tag in such a pair is the *start tag*, and the second is the *end tag* (they are also called *opening tags* and *closing tags*).
[src:pug-templating/html] Another important component is the HTML *document type declaration*, which triggers standards mode rendering.
[src:pug-templating/html] The text between `<html>` and `</html>` describes the web page, and the text between `<body>` and `</body>` is the visible page content.
[src:pug-templating/html] The markup text `<title>This is a title</title>` defines the browser page title shown on browser tabs and window titles and the tag `<div>` defines a division of the page used for easy styling.
[src:pug-templating/html] Between `<head>` and `</head>`, a `<meta>` element can be used to define webpage metadata.
[src:pug-templating/html] The Document Type Declaration `<!DOCTYPE html>` is for HTML5.
[src:pug-templating/html] If a declaration is not included, various browsers will revert to "quirks mode" for rendering.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML documents imply a structure of nested HTML elements.
[src:pug-templating/html] These are indicated in the document by HTML *tags*, enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:pug-templating/html] In the simple, general case, the extent of an element is indicated by a pair of tags: a "start tag" `<p>` and "end tag" `</p>`.
[src:pug-templating/html] The text content of the element, if any, is placed between these tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] Tags may also enclose further tag markup between the start and end, including a mixture of tags and text.
[src:pug-templating/html] This indicates further (nested) elements, as children of the parent element.
[src:pug-templating/html] The start tag may also include the element's *attributes* within the tag.
[src:pug-templating/html] Some elements, such as the line break `<br>` do not permit *any* embedded content, either text or further tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] These require only a single empty tag (akin to a start tag) and do not use an end tag.
[src:pug-templating/html] Many tags, particularly the closing end tag for the very commonly used paragraph element `<p>`, are optional.
[src:pug-templating/html] An HTML browser or other agent can infer the closure for the end of an element from the context and the structural rules defined by the HTML standard.
[src:pug-templating/html] These rules are complex and not widely understood by most HTML authors.
[src:pug-templating/html] The general form of an HTML element is therefore: `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">''content''</tag>`.
[src:pug-templating/html] Some HTML elements are defined as *empty elements* and take the form `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">`.
[src:pug-templating/html] Empty elements may enclose no content, for instance, the `<br>` tag or the inline `<img>` tag.
[src:pug-templating/html] The name of an HTML element is the name used in the tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] The end tag's name is preceded by a slash character `/`.
[src:pug-templating/html] If a tag has no content, an end tag is not allowed.
[src:pug-templating/html] If attributes are not mentioned, default values are used in each case.
[src:pug-templating/html] Header of the HTML document: `<head>...</head>`.
[src:pug-templating/html] CSS can substantially change the rendering.
[src:pug-templating/html] The difference between `<br>` and `<p>` is that `<br>` breaks a line without altering the semantic structure of the page, whereas `<p>` sections the page into paragraphs.
[src:pug-templating/html] The element `<br>` is an *empty element* in that, although it may have attributes, it can take no content and it must not have an end tag.
[src:pug-templating/html] The `href` attribute holds the URL address of the link.
[src:pug-templating/html] Comments can help in the understanding of the markup and do not display in the webpage.
[src:pug-templating/html] Most of the attributes of an element are name–value pairs, separated by `=` and written within the start tag of an element after the element's name.
[src:pug-templating/html] The value may be enclosed in single or double quotes, although values consisting of certain characters can be left unquoted in HTML (but not XHTML).
[src:pug-templating/html] Leaving attribute values unquoted is considered unsafe.
[src:pug-templating/html] In contrast with name-value pair attributes, there are some attributes that affect the element simply by their presence in the start tag of the element, like the `ismap` attribute for the `img` element.
[src:pug-templating/html] Most elements take the language-related attribute `dir` to specify text direction, such as with "rtl" for right-to-left text in, for example, Arabic, Persian or Hebrew.
[src:pug-templating/html] As of version 4.0, HTML defines a set of 252 character entity references and a set of 1,114,050 numeric character references, both of which allow individual characters to be written via simple markup, rather than literally.
[src:pug-templating/html] A literal character and its markup counterpart are considered equivalent and are rendered identically.
[src:pug-templating/html] The ability to "escape" characters in this way allows for the characters `<` and `&` (when written as `&lt;` and `&amp;`, respectively) to be interpreted as character data, rather than markup.
[src:pug-templating/html] For example, a literal `<` normally indicates the start of a tag, and `&` normally indicates the start of a character entity reference or numeric character reference; writing it as `&amp;` or `&#x26;` or `&#38;` allows `&` to be included in the content of an element or in the value of an attribute.
[src:pug-templating/html] The double-quote character (`"`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&quot;` or `&#x22;` or `&#34;` when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:pug-templating/html] Equivalently, the single-quote character (`'`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&#x27;` or `&#39;` (or as `&apos;` in HTML5 or XHTML documents) when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:pug-templating/html] If document authors overlook the need to escape such characters, some browsers can be very forgiving and try to use context to guess their intent.
[src:pug-templating/html] The result is still invalid markup, which makes the document less accessible to other browsers and to other user agents that may try to parse the document for search and indexing purposes for example.
[src:pug-templating/html] Escaping also allows for characters that are not easily typed, or that are not available in the document's character encoding, to be represented within the element and attribute content.
[src:pug-templating/html] Unicode character encodings such as UTF-8 are compatible with all modern browsers and allow direct access to almost all the characters of the world's writing systems.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML defines several data types for element content, such as script data and stylesheet data, and a plethora of types for attribute values, including IDs, names, URIs, numbers, units of length, languages, media descriptors, colors, character encodings, dates and times, and so on.
[src:pug-templating/html] All of these data types are specializations of character data.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML documents are required to start with a document type declaration (informally, a "doctype").
[src:pug-templating/html] In browsers, the doctype helps to define the rendering mode—particularly whether to use quirks mode.
[src:pug-templating/html] The original purpose of the doctype was to enable the parsing and validation of HTML documents by SGML tools based on the document type definition (DTD).
[src:pug-templating/html] The DTD to which the DOCTYPE refers contains a machine-readable grammar specifying the permitted and prohibited content for a document conforming to such a DTD.
[src:pug-templating/html] Browsers, on the other hand, do not implement HTML as an application of SGML and as consequence do not read the DTD.
[src:pug-templating/html] This declaration references the DTD for the "strict" version of HTML 4.01.
[src:pug-templating/html] SGML-based validators read the DTD in order to properly parse the document and to perform validation.
[src:pug-templating/html] In modern browsers, a valid doctype activates standards mode as opposed to quirks mode.
[src:pug-templating/html] In addition, HTML 4.01 provides Transitional and Frameset DTDs, as explained below.
[src:pug-templating/html] The transitional type is the most inclusive, incorporating current tags as well as older or "deprecated" tags, with the Strict DTD excluding deprecated tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] The frameset has all tags necessary to make frames on a page along with the tags included in transitional type.
[src:pug-templating/html] Semantic HTML is a way of writing HTML that emphasizes the meaning of the encoded information over its presentation (look).
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML has included semantic markup from its inception, but has also included presentational markup, such as `<font>`, `<i>`, and `<center>` tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] There are also the semantically neutral div and span tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] Since the late 1990s, when Cascading Style Sheets were beginning to work in most browsers, web authors have been encouraged to avoid the use of presentational HTML markup with a view to the separation of content and presentation.
[src:pug-templating/html] In a 2001 discussion of the Semantic Web, Tim Berners-Lee and others gave examples of ways in which intelligent software "agents" may one day automatically crawl the web and find, filter, and correlate previously unrelated, published facts for the benefit of human users.
[src:pug-templating/html] Such agents are not commonplace even now, but some of the ideas of Web 2.0, mashups and price comparison websites may be coming close.
[src:pug-templating/html] An important type of web agent that does crawl and read web pages automatically, without prior knowledge of what it might find, is the web crawler or search-engine spider.
[src:pug-templating/html] These software agents are dependent on the semantic clarity of web pages they find as they use various techniques and algorithms to read and index millions of web pages a day and provide web users with search facilities without which the World Wide Web's usefulness would be greatly reduced.
[src:pug-templating/html] Presentational markup tags are deprecated in current HTML and XHTML recommendations.
[src:pug-templating/html] The majority of presentational features from previous versions of HTML are no longer allowed as they lead to poorer accessibility, higher cost of site maintenance, and larger document sizes.
[src:pug-templating/html] Good semantic HTML also improves the accessibility of web documents (see also Web Content Accessibility Guidelines).
[src:pug-templating/html] For example, when a screen reader or audio browser can correctly ascertain the structure of a document, it will not waste the visually impaired user's time by reading out repeated or irrelevant information when it has been marked up correctly.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML documents can be delivered by the same means as any other computer file.
[src:pug-templating/html] However, they are most often delivered either by HTTP from a web server or by email.
[src:pug-templating/html] The World Wide Web is composed primarily of HTML documents transmitted from web servers to web browsers using the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:pug-templating/html] However, HTTP is used to serve images, sound, and other content, in addition to HTML.
[src:pug-templating/html] To allow the web browser to know how to handle each document it receives, other information is transmitted along with the document.
[src:pug-templating/html] This meta data usually includes the MIME type (e.g., text/html or application/xhtml+xml) and the character encoding (see Character encodings in HTML).
[src:pug-templating/html] In modern browsers, the MIME type that is sent with the HTML document may affect how the document is initially interpreted.
[src:pug-templating/html] A document sent with the XHTML MIME type is expected to be well-formed XML; syntax errors may cause the browser to fail to render it.
[src:pug-templating/html] The same document sent with the HTML MIME type might be displayed successfully since some browsers are more lenient with HTML.
[src:pug-templating/html] The W3C recommendations state that XHTML 1.0 documents that follow guidelines set forth in the recommendation's Appendix C may be labeled with either MIME Type.
[src:pug-templating/html] XHTML 1.1 also states that XHTML 1.1 documents should be labeled with either MIME type.
[src:pug-templating/html] Most graphical email clients allow the use of a subset of HTML (often ill-defined) to provide formatting and semantic markup not available with plain text.
[src:pug-templating/html] This may include typographic information like colored headings, emphasized and quoted text, inline images and diagrams.
[src:pug-templating/html] Many such clients include both a GUI editor for composing HTML e-mail messages and a rendering engine for displaying them.
[src:pug-templating/html] Use of HTML in e-mail is criticized by some because of compatibility issues, because it can help disguise phishing attacks, because of accessibility issues for blind or visually impaired people, because it can confuse spam filters and because the message size is larger than plain text.
[src:pug-templating/html] The most common filename extension for files containing HTML is .html.
[src:pug-templating/html] A common abbreviation of this is .htm, which originated because some operating systems limit file extensions to three letters.
[src:pug-templating/html] An HTML Application (HTA; file extension .hta) is a Microsoft Windows application that uses HTML and Dynamic HTML in a browser to provide the application's graphical interface.
[src:pug-templating/html] A regular HTML file is confined to the security model of the web browser's security, communicating only to web servers and manipulating only web page objects and site cookies.
[src:pug-templating/html] An HTA runs as a fully trusted application and therefore has more privileges, like creation/editing/removal of files and Windows Registry entries.
[src:pug-templating/html] Because they operate outside the browser's security model, HTAs cannot be executed via HTTP, but must be downloaded (just like an EXE file) and executed from local file system.
[src:pug-templating/html] Since its inception, HTML and its associated protocols gained acceptance relatively quickly.
[src:pug-templating/html] However, no clear standards existed in the early years of the language.
[src:pug-templating/html] Though its creators originally conceived of HTML as a semantic language devoid of presentation details, practical uses pushed many presentational elements and attributes into the language, driven largely by the various browser vendors.
[src:pug-templating/html] The latest standards surrounding HTML reflect efforts to overcome the sometimes chaotic development of the language and to create a rational foundation for building both meaningful and well-presented documents.
[src:pug-templating/html] To return HTML to its role as a semantic language, the W3C has developed style languages such as CSS and XSL to shoulder the burden of presentation.
[src:pug-templating/html] In conjunction, the HTML specification has slowly reined in the presentational elements.
[src:pug-templating/html] There are two axes differentiating various variations of HTML as currently specified: SGML-based HTML versus XML-based HTML (referred to as XHTML) on one axis, and strict versus transitional (loose) versus frameset on the other axis.
[src:pug-templating/html] One difference in the latest HTML specifications lies in the distinction between the SGML-based specification and the XML-based specification.
[src:pug-templating/html] The XML-based specification is usually called XHTML to distinguish it clearly from the more traditional definition.
[src:pug-templating/html] However, the root element name continues to be "html" even in the XHTML-specified HTML.
[src:pug-templating/html] The W3C intended XHTML 1.0 to be identical to HTML 4.01 except where limitations of XML over the more complex SGML require workarounds.
[src:pug-templating/html] Because XHTML and HTML are closely related, they are sometimes documented in parallel.
[src:pug-templating/html] In such circumstances, some authors conflate the two names as (X)HTML or X(HTML).
[src:pug-templating/html] Like HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0 has three sub-specifications: strict, transitional, and frameset.
[src:pug-templating/html] Aside from the different opening declarations for a document, the differences between an HTML 4.01 and XHTML 1.0 document—in each of the corresponding DTDs—are largely syntactic.
[src:pug-templating/html] The underlying syntax of HTML allows many shortcuts that XHTML does not, such as elements with optional opening or closing tags, and even empty elements which must not have an end tag.
[src:pug-templating/html] By contrast, XHTML requires all elements to have an opening tag and a closing tag.
[src:pug-templating/html] XHTML, however, also introduces a new shortcut: an XHTML tag may be opened and closed within the same tag, by including a slash before the end of the tag like this: `<br/>`.
[src:pug-templating/html] The introduction of this shorthand, which is not used in the SGML declaration for HTML 4.01, may confuse earlier software unfamiliar with this new convention.
[src:pug-templating/html] A fix for this is remove the slash preceding the closing angle bracket, as such: `<br>`.
[src:pug-templating/html] To understand the subtle differences between HTML and XHTML, consider the transformation of a valid and well-formed XHTML 1.0 document that adheres to Appendix C (see below) into a valid HTML 4.01 document.
[src:pug-templating/html] Change the document type declaration from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:pug-templating/html] Ensure that the document's MIME type is set to `text/html`.
[src:pug-templating/html] For both HTML and XHTML, this comes from the HTTP `Content-Type` header sent by the server.
[src:pug-templating/html] Change the XML empty-element syntax to an HTML style empty element (`<br/>` to `<br>`).
[src:pug-templating/html] Those are the main changes necessary to translate a document from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:pug-templating/html] To translate from HTML to XHTML would also require the addition of any omitted opening or closing tags.
[src:pug-templating/html] Whether coding in HTML or XHTML it may just be best to always include the optional tags within an HTML document rather than remembering which tags can be omitted.
[src:pug-templating/html] A well-formed XHTML document adheres to all the syntax requirements of XML.
[src:pug-templating/html] A valid document adheres to the content specification for XHTML, which describes the document structure.
[src:pug-templating/html] The W3C recommends several conventions to ensure an easy migration between HTML and XHTML.
[src:pug-templating/html] By carefully following the W3C's compatibility guidelines, a user agent should be able to interpret the document equally as HTML or XHTML.
[src:pug-templating/html] For documents that are XHTML 1.0 and have been made compatible in this way, the W3C permits them to be served either as HTML (with a `text/html` MIME type), or as XHTML (with an `application/xhtml+xml` or `application/xml` MIME type).
[src:pug-templating/html] When delivered as XHTML, browsers should use an XML parser, which adheres strictly to the XML specifications for parsing the document's contents.
[src:pug-templating/html] HTML 4 defined three different versions of the language: Strict, Transitional (once called Loose), and Frameset.
[src:pug-templating/html] The Strict version is intended for new documents and is considered best practice, while the Transitional and Frameset versions were developed to make it easier to transition documents that conformed to older HTML specifications or did not conform to any specification to a version of HTML 4.
[src:pug-templating/html] The Transitional and Frameset versions allow for presentational markup, which is omitted in the Strict version.
[src:pug-templating/html] Instead, cascading style sheets are encouraged to improve the presentation of HTML documents.
[src:pug-templating/html] Because XHTML 1 only defines an XML syntax for the language defined by HTML 4, the same differences apply to XHTML 1 as well.
[src:pug-templating/html] The Frameset version includes everything in the Transitional version, as well as the `frameset` element (used instead of `body`) and the `frame` element.
[src:pug-templating/html] In addition to the above transitional differences, the frameset specifications (whether XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01) specify a different content model, with `frameset` replacing `body`, that contains either `frame` elements, or optionally `noframes` with a `body`.
[src:pug-templating/html] As this list demonstrates, the loose versions of the specification are maintained for legacy support.
[src:pug-templating/html] However, contrary to popular misconceptions, the move to XHTML does not imply a removal of this legacy support.
[src:pug-templating/html] Rather the X in XML stands for extensible and the W3C is modularizing the entire specification and opens it up to independent extensions.
[src:pug-templating/html] The primary achievement in the move from XHTML 1.0 to XHTML 1.1 is the modularization of the entire specification.
[src:pug-templating/html] The strict version of HTML is deployed in XHTML 1.1 through a set of modular extensions to the base XHTML 1.1 specification.
[src:pug-templating/html] Likewise, someone looking for the loose (transitional) or frameset specifications will find similar extended XHTML 1.1 support (much of it is contained in the legacy or frame modules).
[src:pug-templating/html] Modularization also allows for separate features to develop on their own timetable.
[src:pug-templating/html] So for example, XHTML 1.1 will allow quicker migration to emerging XML standards such as MathML (a presentational and semantic math language based on XML) and XForms—a new highly advanced web-form technology to replace the existing HTML forms.
[src:pug-templating/html] In summary, the HTML 4 specification primarily reined in all the various HTML implementations into a single clearly written specification based on SGML.
[src:pug-templating/html] XHTML 1.0, ported this specification, as is, to the new XML-defined specification.
[src:pug-templating/html] Next, XHTML 1.1 takes advantage of the extensible nature of XML and modularizes the whole specification.
[src:pug-templating/html] XHTML 2.0 was intended to be the first step in adding new features to the specification in a standards-body-based approach.
[src:pug-templating/html] The HTML Living Standard, which is developed by WHATWG, is the official version, while W3C HTML5 is no longer separate from WHATWG.
[src:pug-templating/html] WYSIWYG editors (*what you see is what you get*), are HTML editors in which the user lays out everything as it is to appear in the HTML document using a graphical user interface (GUI), such as Microsoft FrontPage, often similar to word processors.
[src:pug-templating/html] The editor renders the document rather than showing the code, so authors do not require extensive knowledge of HTML.
[src:pug-templating/html] The WYSIWYG editing model has been criticized, primarily because of the low quality of the generated code; there are various developers advocating a change to the WYSIWYM model (*what you see is what you mean*).
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:pug-templating/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] A **template processor** (also known as a **template engine** or **template parser**) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] The language that the templates are written in is known as a **template language** or **templating language**.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Template engines typically include features common to most high-level programming languages, with an emphasis on features for processing plain text.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] The templating languages are generally simple substitution-only languages, in contrast to the more sophisticated facilities in full-blown template processors, but may contain some logic.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Simple examples include ‘printf’ print format strings, found in many programming languages, and snippets, found in a number of text editors and source code editors.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] In word processors, templates are a common feature, while automatic filling in of the templates is often referred to as mail merge.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] An illustrative example of the complementary nature of parsing and templating is the `s` (substitute) command in the sed text processor, originating from search-and-replace in the ed text editor.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] For example, `s/(cat|dog)s?/\1s/g` replaces all occurrences of "cat" or "dog" with "cats" or "dogs", without duplicating an existing "s": `(cat|dog)` is the 1st (and only) sub-expression in the regexp, and `\1` in the format string substitutes this into the output.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] This may be a relational database, a source file such as XML, an alternate format of flat file database, a spreadsheet or any of other various sources of preformatted data.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Some template processing systems are limited in the types of data that can be used.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Others are designed for maximum flexibility and allow many different types of data.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Additionally some template engines allow additional configuration options.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] These may consist of an entire document or a document fragment.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Template processing is used in various contexts for different purposes.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] The specific purpose is ordinarily contingent upon the software application or template engine in use.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] However, the flexibility of template processing systems often enables unconventional uses for purposes not originally intended by the original designers.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] A **template engine** is a specific kind of template processing module that exhibits all of the major features of a modern programming language.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] The term *template engine* evolved as a generalized description of programming languages whose primary or exclusive purpose was to process templates and data to output text.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] The use of this term is most notably applied to web development using a web template system, and it is also applied to other contexts as well.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Document generation frameworks typically use template processing as the central model for generating documents.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] A web template engine processes web templates and source data (typically from a relational database) to produce one or more output web pages or page fragments.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] It is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Currently, template processing software is most frequently used in the context of development for the web.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] XSLT is a template processing model designed by W3C.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] It is designed primarily for transformations on XML data (into web documents or other output).
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Programming languages such as Perl, Python, PHP, Ruby, C#, Java, and Go support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] JavaServer Pages, Active Server Pages, Genshi (for Python), and eRuby are examples of template engines designed specifically for web application development.
[src:pug-templating/template-processor] Moreover, template processing is sometimes included as a sub-feature of software packages like text editors, IDEs and relational database management systems.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:pug-templating/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
